The paper discusses the battery management system, which is a key component of smart grids, microgrids, and electric mobility. The proposed model is based on a mechanical analogy, which suggests that the paper may belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. The paper also discusses the use of an extended Kalman filter (EKF) as a nonlinear state estimator, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.ET (Embedded Systems) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a multicell EKF system, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.EM (Electric Machines and Drives) sub-category. The paper also proposes a novel cell model and a procedure for parameters estimation, which suggests that it may belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the battery management system, which is a software system, suggesting that it may belong to the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category.
